{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491684"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:58:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:58:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1021"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1021"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.18,0.66,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1021"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74895"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"611"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"9315"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44491"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents with a six month history of an intermittent ache and discharge between his buttocks. His underpants are regularly stained with white material. He is otherwise well with no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is a 3 mm opening in the midline 5 cm posterior to the anus. This area is indurated with some adjacent scar tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hidradenitis suppurativa","Anal fistula","Pilonidal sinus","Epidermoid (sebaceous) cyst","Anal fissure"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is almost certainly a \u003Cstrong\u003Epilonidal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E. Pilonidal disease typically occurs in young white men, who are often obese and have a sedentary lifestyle. There may be a range of presentations from small, asymptomatic hair-containing cysts to large sacrococcygeal abscesses. They can present in a chronic form, with mucoid or purulent discharge. More typically they present with recurrent bouts of pain and bloody discharge. It is thought that this condition is the result of hair penetrating the subcutaneous tissues with subsequent sinus formation. Nests of hairs are a common finding in these sinuses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E can have a similar mode of presentation in terms of discharge and acute inflammation, this would be an uncommon site for these cysts. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnal fissures\u003C/strong\u003E occur most commonly in the posterior midline (85-90%) however these are in the anal canal and are associated with significant pain on defecation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnal fistula \u003C/strong\u003Eoccur in closer proximity to the anal verge and the discharge would be darker. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHidradenitis suppurativa\u003C/strong\u003E is a disorder of the follicular epithelium in the apocrine gland regions of the skin tends and is found in the axillae or groin regions. It is typically associated with multiple painful, discharging lumps.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pilonidal sinus can have a range of presentations from small, asymptomatic hair-containing cysts to large sacrococcygeal abscesses"],"references":["Thompson MR, Senapati A, Kitchen P. Simple day-case surgery for pilonidal sinus disease. Br J Surg 2011;98:198-209. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21125608/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74895"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1021"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74895"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:41:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:41:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1021"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90832"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group